{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"d8218533f8889021c61c167d38f418acfa5bd0a7524af739fa763fc3717b4322","slug":"pages.m14-confidence-intervals-for-the-population-mean-5","location":"/pages/187-m14-confidence-intervals-for-the-population-mean-5-of-8.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Confidence Intervals for the Population Mean (5 of 8)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"thumbnail":"/textbook/build/image069-7d019089f6d9383f3b8872233ca423d8.gif","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"187-m14-confidence-intervals-for-the-population-mean-5-of-8.md","url":"/textbook/build/187-m14-confidence-i-7a37d3aa5d194331f8747a6c67d88500.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"QWdwRDosfT"}],"key":"pg3v3JUEQS"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Explain what a confidence interval represents and determine how changes in sample size and confidence level affect the precision of the confidence interval.\n- Find confidence intervals for the population mean and the population proportion (when certain conditions are met), and perform sample size calculations.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"paEYTgzbYO"}],"key":"XJOTNPc3g4"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let us now go back to the confidence interval for the mean, and more specifically, to the question that we posed at the beginning of the previous page:","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"gzQgyPXP8O"}],"key":"LDBE0WZQlC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Is there a way to increase the precision of the confidence interval (i.e., make it narrower) ","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"MtpWSIRwoX"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"without","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"wFyoDlZ3Dr"}],"key":"fT1cqHmJ0p"},{"type":"text","value":" compromising on the level of confidence?","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"YWc8b02uQc"}],"key":"KZH0M3soWT"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Since the width of the confidence interval is a function of its margin of error, let’s look closely at the margin of error of the confidence interval for the mean and see how it can be reduced:","position":{"start":{"line":12,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"key":"MoGDQ0MC66"}],"key":"UtGieKyRx9"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"inlineMath","value":"z^{\\times}\\times\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>z</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mi>σ</mi><msqrt><mi>n</mi></msqrt></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">z^{\\times}\\times\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8547em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2334em;vertical-align:-0.538em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6954em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.6259em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord sqrt mtight\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8059em;\"><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mtight\" style=\"padding-left:0.833em;\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.7659em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail mtight\" style=\"min-width:0.853em;height:1.08em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='1.08em' viewBox='0 0 400000 1080' preserveAspectRatio='xMinYMin slice'><path d='M95,702\nc-2.7,0,-7.17,-2.7,-13.5,-8c-5.8,-5.3,-9.5,-10,-9.5,-14\nc0,-2,0.3,-3.3,1,-4c1.3,-2.7,23.83,-20.7,67.5,-54\nc44.2,-33.3,65.8,-50.3,66.5,-51c1.3,-1.3,3,-2,5,-2c4.7,0,8.7,3.3,12,10\ns173,378,173,378c0.7,0,35.3,-71,104,-213c68.7,-142,137.5,-285,206.5,-429\nc69,-144,104.5,-217.7,106.5,-221\nl0 -0\nc5.3,-9.3,12,-14,20,-14\nH400000v40H845.2724\ns-225.272,467,-225.272,467s-235,486,-235,486c-2.7,4.7,-9,7,-19,7\nc-6,0,-10,-1,-12,-3s-194,-422,-194,-422s-65,47,-65,47z\nM834 80h400000v40h-400000z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2341em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">σ</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.538em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"ZnOUh3JtJJ"}],"key":"Nh4Sj4fyuK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Since z* controls the level of confidence, we can rephrase our question above in the following way:","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"c0AfcFBLzB"}],"key":"gRaJQlg4t4"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Is there a way to reduce this margin of error other than by reducing z*?","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"vlnmyEqEkd"}],"key":"RI7lkq9A7u"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you look closely at the margin of error, you’ll see that the answer is yes. We can do that by increasing the sample size n (since it appears in the denominator).","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"AgmoUWkPK9"}],"key":"aBg3UDdEHe"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"ZR4eVpzya1"}],"key":"QEUvyuMeqZ"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Many Students Wonder**\n\nConfidence Intervals for the Population Mean\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"rMi0MsArSZ"}],"key":"ODGxKeeaYs"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s look at an example first and then explain why increasing the sample size is a way to increase the precision of the confidence interval ","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"R63Gf9uOfL"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"without","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"TDXco4y3JR"}],"key":"DlmCuEFmz6"},{"type":"text","value":" compromising on the level of confidence.","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"dkqqhI05fH"}],"key":"ofFqX9Tc7M"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"key":"ee8e8eJSNh"}],"key":"rqkiXVt8iJ"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"Recall the IQ example:\n\nThe IQ level of students at a particular university has an unknown mean (μ) and a known standard deviation of $\\sigma=15$. A simple random sample of 100 students is found to have the sample mean IQ $\\bar{x}=115$. A 95% confidence interval for μ in this case is:\n\n$\\bar{x}\\pm2\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}=115\\pm2\\left(\\frac{15}{\\sqrt{100}}\\right)=115\\pm3.0=\\left(112, 118\\right)$\n\nNote that the margin of error is m = 3, and therefore the width of the confidence interval is 6.\n\nNow, what if we change the problem slightly by increasing the sample size, and assume that it was 400 instead of 100?\n\n```{figure} images/image067.gif\n:alt: A large circle represents the Population of all Students at SU. We are interested in the variable IQ, and the unknown parameter is μ, the population mean IQ level. In addition, we know that σ = 15. From this population we create a sample of size n=400, represented by a smaller circle. In this sample, we find that x bar = 115.\n\nA large circle represents the Population of all Students at SU. We are interested in the variable IQ, and the unknown parameter is μ, the population mean IQ level. In addition, we know that σ = 15. From this population we create a sample of size n=400, represented by a smaller circle. In this sample, we find that x bar = 115.\n```\n\nIn this case, the 95% confidence interval for μ is:\n\n$\\bar{x}\\pm2\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}=115\\pm2\\left(\\frac{15}{\\sqrt{400}}\\right)=115\\pm1.5=\\left(113.5, 116.5\\right)$\n\nThe margin of error here is only m = 1.5, and thus the width is only 3.\n\nNote that for the same level of confidence (95%) we now have a narrower, and thus more precise, confidence interval.","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"V4kaNGqocn"}],"key":"GgNAnETNN3"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s try to understand why a larger sample size will reduce the margin of error for a fixed level of confidence. There are three ways to explain it: mathematically, using probability theory, and intuitively.","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"b1nSE5OiNy"}],"key":"lRnZeI2Lp3"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We’ve already alluded to the mathematical explanation; the margin of error is ","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"key":"h2HYo1Ectu"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"z^{*}\\times\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>z</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">∗</mo></msup><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mi>σ</mi><msqrt><mi>n</mi></msqrt></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">z^{*}\\times\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.772em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2334em;vertical-align:-0.538em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6954em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.6259em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord sqrt mtight\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8059em;\"><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mtight\" style=\"padding-left:0.833em;\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.7659em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"hide-tail mtight\" style=\"min-width:0.853em;height:1.08em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width='400em' height='1.08em' viewBox='0 0 400000 1080' preserveAspectRatio='xMinYMin slice'><path d='M95,702\nc-2.7,0,-7.17,-2.7,-13.5,-8c-5.8,-5.3,-9.5,-10,-9.5,-14\nc0,-2,0.3,-3.3,1,-4c1.3,-2.7,23.83,-20.7,67.5,-54\nc44.2,-33.3,65.8,-50.3,66.5,-51c1.3,-1.3,3,-2,5,-2c4.7,0,8.7,3.3,12,10\ns173,378,173,378c0.7,0,35.3,-71,104,-213c68.7,-142,137.5,-285,206.5,-429\nc69,-144,104.5,-217.7,106.5,-221\nl0 -0\nc5.3,-9.3,12,-14,20,-14\nH400000v40H845.2724\ns-225.272,467,-225.272,467s-235,486,-235,486c-2.7,4.7,-9,7,-19,7\nc-6,0,-10,-1,-12,-3s-194,-422,-194,-422s-65,47,-65,47z\nM834 80h400000v40h-400000z'/></svg></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2341em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">σ</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.538em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"XUfnEUZntw"},{"type":"text","value":", and since n, the sample size, appears in the denominator, increasing n will reduce the margin of error.","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"key":"CbBEOzcveL"}],"key":"vp5hWZ1vHp"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As we saw in our discussion about point estimates, probability theory tells us that","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"key":"uUEGPcpjUP"}],"key":"xIJIiMHHuo"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/textbook/build/image069-7d019089f6d9383f3b8872233ca423d8.gif","alt":"Two sampling distribution curves for x-bar. One is squished down and wider, while the other is much taller and narrower. Both curves share the same μ. The tall, narrow distribution was based on a larger sample size, which has a smaller standard deviation, and so is less spread out. This means that values of x-bar are more likely to be closer to μ when the sample size is larger.","key":"kfXv2veUG4","urlSource":"images/image069.gif"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Two sampling distribution curves for x-bar. One is squished down and wider, while the other is much taller and narrower. Both curves share the same μ. The tall, narrow distribution was based on a larger sample size, which has a smaller standard deviation, and so is less spread out. This means that values of x-bar are more likely to be closer to μ when the sample size is larger.","position":{"start":{"line":67,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"xtsim1bB2o"}],"key":"xq16ZM9tQt"}],"key":"wAxFiWgIpP"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"ICJbs88qYf"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This explains why with a larger sample size the margin of error (which represents how far apart we believe ","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"JMc9UcCeVR"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\bar{x}","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>x</mi><mo>ˉ</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bar{x}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5678em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.5678em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.2222em;\"><span class=\"mord\">ˉ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"irekD7lEsI"},{"type":"text","value":" might be from μ for a given level of confidence) is smaller.","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"rhTUV3RF31"}],"key":"B2Lq2Htn9U"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"On an intuitive level, if our estimate ","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"key":"u1emC3Bgz9"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\bar{x}","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>x</mi><mo>ˉ</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bar{x}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5678em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.5678em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.2222em;\"><span class=\"mord\">ˉ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"QoxCwKnJFl"},{"type":"text","value":" is based on a larger sample (i.e., a larger fraction of the population), we have more faith in it, or it is more reliable, and therefore we need to account for less error around it.","position":{"start":{"line":72,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"key":"ngKthVE189"}],"key":"B5W3HbyD2f"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Comment","position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"key":"DHgN2KQX53"}],"identifier":"comment","label":"Comment","html_id":"comment","implicit":true,"key":"KtVwtLiKIl"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":76,"column":1},"end":{"line":76,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"While it is true that for a given level of confidence, increasing the sample size increases the precision of our interval estimation, in practice, increasing the sample size is not always possible. Consider a study in which there is a non-negligible cost involved for collecting data from each participant (an expensive medical procedure, for example). If the study has some budgetary constraints, which is usually the case, increasing the sample size from 100 to 400 is just not possible in terms of cost-effectiveness. Another instance in which increasing the sample size is impossible is when a larger sample is simply not available, even if we had the money to afford it. For example, consider a study on the effectiveness of a drug on curing a very rare disease among children. Since the disease is rare, there are a limited number of children who could be participants. This is the reality of statistics. Sometimes theory collides with reality, and you just do the best you can.","position":{"start":{"line":76,"column":1},"end":{"line":76,"column":1}},"key":"DovIVeBs5r"}],"key":"wsw2rKiVPF"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"sMgNJQoUup"}],"key":"HdVKkIp6Ka"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":79,"column":1},"end":{"line":81,"column":1}},"key":"gas1l3lUgA"}],"key":"CpEuX3yBd5"}],"key":"LMghLAbZpF"}],"key":"DZVU7u6j3v"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Confidence Intervals for the Population Mean (4 of 8)","url":"/pages/m14-confidence-intervals-for-the-population-mean-4","group":"Unit 5: Inference"},"next":{"title":"Confidence Intervals for the Population Mean (6 of 8)","url":"/pages/m14-confidence-intervals-for-the-population-mean-6","group":"Unit 5: Inference"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3002"}